<DOCNO> AP900704-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
with a regularity that overwhelms 
unloading crews trains are trundling grain to afghanistan in the 
first un operations ever based in the soviet union 
soviet officials stunned an international meeting in 1988 by 
offering 400 million rubles for a un program within their borders 
to supply food and relief goods to northern afghanistan 
un and soviet officials admit the program has been fraught 
with difficulties but call it a success and a good start toward 
soviet involvement in humanitarian aid elsewhere 
you saw the summit agreement on ethiopia said nikolai 
skripka a foreign ministry expert in moscow expressing enthusiasm 
over the new soviet role in un and international relief 
presidents bush and mikhail s gorbachev agreed to help starving 
ethiopians with american food transported by the soviet union 
the afghan program is part of operation salam the un 
coordinating office for afghanistan headed by the former high 
commissioner for refugees prince sadruddin aga khan 
operation salam operates mostly from pakistan and iran with 
base camps in afghanistan and an overall budget of more than 1 
billion the soviet component in considered crucial 
we have no other way to get to people in the north because of 
fighting or logistical problems sadruddin said access through 
the soviet union has made all the difference 
the first un field office on soviet territory is a discreet 
compound tucked under shade trees in this somnambulant uzbekistan 
border town the hottest spot in the soviet union 
people often overlook us because we have no refugees but the 
implications here are extremely important said olivier allais a 
french television producer turned diplomat 
gesturing toward the map allais indicated a broad range of 
crossborder operations along the frontier 
un workers channel food monitor health conditions and train 
development teams they are helping afghans combat a locust attack 
that threatens the seasons food crop 
allais also supervises each salam express special trains that 
speed relief to the border 
grain is loaded in bulk at helsinki finland and carried via 
leningrad across the breadth of the soviet union to friendship 
bridge a vast span put up to facilitate moving red army units into 
afghanistan 
trains go straight to a bagging plant across the border at 
hairaton where un officials say lackadaisical afghan crews 
slowed by restricted summer hours run far behind schedule 
some sacks are returned to termez and trucked north to dushanbe 
for distribution across remote border points altogether un 
officials expect to distribute 35000 tons of western grain 
moscows un role separate from its direct aid to the afghan 
government is a delicate balance 
un volunteers help afghans clear the uncounted and uncharted 
mines left behind when soviet troops in 1988 after nearly 10 years 
in afghanistan no soviet un workers cross the border 
food is routed into local afghan markets with no attempt to 
influence whether it reaches governmentcontrolled or rebel areas 
some goes to vulnerable groups mainly families of guerrillas 
most areas supplied from the north are under guerrilla control 
but food reaches both sides un officials said 
the soviets support the program even though they backed the 
kabul government in its war with the moslem insurgents 
skripka the foreign ministry official in moscow made sure a 
reporter saw a villagers quote reported in the operation salam 
newsletter it said 
when the soviets came with guns and tried to impose themselves 
on us we fought if they now want to come as friends they are 
welcome 
one of the biggest problems is a centrally controlled soviet 
system that sometimes drives un workers to footstamping rage 
each step must be approved by a cabinet minister who delegates 
officials to recruit state enterprises 
in one operation a un official found his trucking contract 
did not cover unloading or storage he found space in a warehouse 
yard but had to negotiate another contract for guards 
one day when rain clouds gathered he realized he needed yet 
another contract for tarpaulins to save the emergency food from 
ruin 
if the offices single approved rubber stamp is taken to 
dushanbe for the signing of a contract business halts in termez 
allais has waited six months to buy the office a small sedan 
with soviet rubles refusing to honor the local custom of greasing 
the wheels with a bribe 
it can be frustrating he said and smiled at what he 
acknowledged was a gross understatement but this is something 
the un has never done before we are learning how to make use of 
this huge soviet economy 
at the same time he said soviet officials took pains to help 
operation salam showing enthusiasm for a sort of international 
cooperation unthinkable before gorbachev 
they have approved field offices along the afghan border and new 
operations by unicef the world health organization and unesco to 
work with afghans 
this is a start but we are anxious to do what we can 
skripka said producing a fat white book of project papers he 
brought back from an operation salam meeting in geneva 
allais is hoping success in termez will hasten followup programs 
and reinforcements he covers the border with a single un deputy 
four un volunteers a soviet office manager and a secretary a 
world food program officer supervises grain shipments 
this is an important step for the soviets allais said 
without operations from here all of northern afghanistan would 
be neglected 
</TEXT>
