<TEXT>
here at a glance is albania its people geography and its 
political history 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
3201000 1989 estimate 
ethnic breakdown albanians gegs in the north and tosks in the 
south 96 percent greeks 25 percent 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
11100 square miles slightly larger than the state of maryland 
located in southeastern europe on the coast of the adriatic sea 
neighbors greece on the south yugoslavia on the northeast 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
industries chemical fertilizer textiles 
chief crops corn wheat cotton potatoes tobacco citrus 
fruits grapes 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
legislature of 250 deputies meets a few days a year essentially to 
ratify actions taken in its name by the presidium of the assembly 
headed by ramiz alia the head of state 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
1945 elections are held based on a single slate of candidates 
spnsored by the communists headed by enver hoxha 
1946 king zog is deposed and the peoples republic of albania 
was proclaimed 
1949 albania fearing yugoslavian expansionism joins the 
moscowbased cmea council for mutual economic assistance or 
comecom 
1955 albania joins the warsaw pact 
1961 the soviet union denounces albanias ties with beijing 
and breaks relations 
1962 albania withdraws from the cmea and turns increasingly to 
the peoples republic of china for support 
1968 albania withdraws from the warsaw pact 
1972 following improvement of relations between china and the 
usa albania becomes disenchanted with beijing 
1978 beijing formally terminated all economic and military 
support of albania 
1985 enver hoxha dies and is replaced by ramiz alia who vows 
to continue hoxhas policies 
1987 ramiz alia reelected as president of the presidium and 
head of the party of labor of albania communist party 
1989 although reforms are sweeping away the repressive 
governments of eastern europe alia continues with the hardline 
stalinist goverment that has been in place since world war ii 
1990 riots break out in tirana when albanians seek sanctuary 
in foreign embassies in an apparent attempt to flee albanias 
repressive regime 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

