<TEXT>
members of congress say they want assurances 
from the energy department that dramatic cost increases in cleaning 
up nuclear weapons waste will yield a safer environment not bigger 
profits for contractors 
the department said tuesday it will take about 50 percent more 
money and twice as many people as earlier projected to clean up 
radioactive waste at weapons plants over the next five years 
i think there is support on the capitol hill for this but 
people are going to start asking what is being cleaned up what is 
being accomplished rep norm dicks dwash said tuesday 
i worry about how much of the money is going into the pockets 
of the contractors and how much actual cleanup is being done he 
said 
the report said cleanup will cost about 6 billion in each of 
the next five years it said the extra costs mostly resulted from 
the discovery of additional waste as well as tougher regulations 
that make the government and its contractors more vulnerable to 
lawsuits 
the revised fiveyear total through fiscal year 1995 will exceed 
286 billion compared with the 195 billion the energy 
department estimated in november the report said 
the price tag for 19921996 totals 316 billion an estimate 
that had not been available previously the general accounting 
office an investigative arm of congress has predicted the overall 
cleanup bill will total 150 billion to 200 billion over the next 
30 years 
there is nothing close to the required infrastructure 
available to manage and implement these solutions the doe report 
said adding that all of the departments program offices were 
understaffed 
it said cleanup staff should be increased from 437 fulltime 
employees to more than 1000 adding that the demand for personnel 
could easily take a decade to supply 
leo duffy director of does office of environmental restoration 
and waste management said some of the costs may have been inflated 
for planning purposes and that the department will be seeking ways 
to reduce them 
but he also noted that costs could rise as scientists discover 
additional contaminants produced at plants since world war ii 
i hope everyone realizes we are at the embryonic stage of 
developing a plan to try to solve a 40year backlog about 75 
percent of the program is remedial investigation which means we 
are looking at each site to determine what the problems are he 
said 
rep tom bevill dala chairman of the house appropriations 
subcommittee that oversees doe said lawmakers are not going to 
just throw money at the problem 
but i think congress will be very supportive of anything 
dealing with the environment in this decade because our track 
record has not been so good in the past and people are now starting 
to realize it he said 
sen john glenn dohio whose attention to the issue has been 
credited with much of the departments recent activity said he was 
not the least bit surprised by the escalating costs 
after all this is a problem that has been ignored for 40 
years he said this is a problem that should have priority 
because it is the most dangerous we have to make a start set 
priorities and get going 
doe clearly needs more money to deal with the problem but 
they also need more people who are skilled and talented enough to 
handle the problem said rep john spratt jr dsc chairman 
of a special house armed services committee task force on nuclear 
weapons 
in a few years if the department has no real fruit to show 
for all its expenditures the support might fall off he said 
