<TEXT>
a legal foundation asked a federal judge 
tuesday to forbid earth first from holding its annual gathering in 
a montana forest saying the us forest service illegally issued 
the environmental group a permit 
the denverbased mountain states legal foundation is seeking a 
permanent injunction barring the july 715 gathering in beaverhead 
national forest in southwestern montana 
us district judge charles lovell took the foundations request 
under advisement and indicated he would decide later this week 
whether the permit was legal 
the foundation and 77 other groups representing ranchers 
loggers miners and offroad vehicle users say the service should 
not allow earth first in the forest saying the group advocates 
illegal sabotage against developers of wildlands 
we know who these people are we know what they want to do 
william pendley an attorney for foundation told lovell 
pendley argued that earth first encourages treespiking the 
spiking of motorcycle trails harassment of survey crews 
destruction of logging equipment and other sabotage he presented 
copies of pages from an earth first publication that contained 
detailed instructions on these acts 
lovell agreed that treespiking and other acts of sabotage were 
serious crimes but asked pendley for evidence that those attending 
the gathering planned to commit such acts 
pendley said he had no evidence that illegal activities would 
occur at the gathering but said what we have is evidence of what 
they have done in the past 
in a complaint filed monday the foundation said the forest 
service should prepare an environmental impact statement on the 
earth first request 
however assistant us attorney bernie hubley argued tuesday the 
group would be easier to control under the permit 
without a permit the forest service says the impact on the 
environment would be even more unpredictable hubley told lovell 
hubley said the forest service not only followed the law in 
issuing the permit but also decided it would be in the publics 
best interest to have earth first members meeting at one 
controlled site 
organizers of next weeks round river rendezvous in the 
beaverhead forest say theyre expecting hundreds of earth first 
members from across the country 
pendley said his clients were worried about possible harm to 
timber cattle and other resources 
hubley said those fears are unfounded and that the foundation 
and fellow plaintiffs therefore had no standing to ask for an 
injunction 
philip knight an earth first member in bozeman who helped 
organize the gathering said it would go forward regardless of the 
court case 
i dont see any way they can stop it he said monday word 
has gone out all over the country and there are people from all 
over the country coming to it well meet without the permit if 
we have to 
knight said earth first cannot control actions by all of its 
members and said the group as a whole shouldnt be penalized for 
the actions of a few 
at past rendezvouses there have been no such incidents 
involved he said anyone engaging in it i condemn them right 
now 
beaverhead national forest officials approved a permit in april 
for earth first to gather on a 30acre site and required the 
group to post a 1000 bond and prepare an emergency medical plan 
for those attending knight said earth first has complied with the 
requirements 
