<TEXT>
the air line pilots association says it will 
ask federal investigators to reconsider their conclusion that the 
pilot of usair flight 5050 caused the plane to skid into new yorks 
east river 
the national transportation safety board determined tuesday that 
the sept 20 1989 crash that killed two passengers probably was 
caused by the pilots failure to detect a rudder control problem as 
well as pilot errors in aborting the takeoff 
the board said that despite the problem with the rudder setting 
simulator tests showed the new boeing 737400 could either have 
taken off safely or aborted its landing without going into the 
river 
fiftyfive passengers and six crew members were rescued from the 
river after the plane slid and split apart off the end of the 
laguardia airport runway 
the pilots union protested the boards decision calling it a 
total travesty and said it would appeal to the board for 
reconsideration board conclusions and recommendations carry no 
force of law but serve only to advise other agencies on steps to 
take for ensuring safety 
tom kreamer a usair pilot who spoke for the union said the 
board should have blamed the crash on a design error in the planes 
control panel that allowed a rudder trim control to be improperly 
set 
boeing played an integral part in this accident said 
kreamer 
the trim control determines the neutral setting for the rudder 
after the crash boeing and federal aviation administration 
officials ordered changes in the controls to prevent them from 
accidentally being reset by visitors in the cockpit or objects laid 
on the console 
the board said it could not determine how the rudder trim became 
set in the fullleft position before the usair jet taxied onto the 
runway 
this lays a tremendous burden on one individual in a very 
complex system said board member john lauber 
but lauber with nods of agreement from other board members 
said the conclusion was justified because there were so many lapses 
on the part of pilot michael martin during the incident 
martin aborted the takeoff as the plane started to drift to the 
left with copilot constantin kleissas at the controls for the first 
time on a commercial 737 flight 
the board cited the pilots decision to let his inexperienced 
copilot control the nighttime takeoff martins failure to engage 
an automatic braking system miscommunication in the cockpit 
improper use of nosewheel steering and the failure to have air 
speeds called out during takeoff 
the faa suspended martin and kleissas licenses and the agency 
was critical of their failure to appear for drug tests immediately 
after the crash tests two days later were negative 
both men dropped appeals of the suspension they continue to 
work for usair and will be allowed to fly again if they pass 
recertification tests 
board member jim burnett joined in the 40 vote but filed an 
additional assertion that usairs failure to assign an adequately 
prepared and seasoned flight crew was a contributing factor in 
the crash 
burnett said the board did not cite design of the control knob 
as a factor because the pilot had so many chances to discover and 
correct it and because boeing and the faa already were correcting 
the problem 
 
