<TEXT>
schools in los angeles minneapolis and rochester 
ny will be transformed into professional practice schools 
where fledgling teachers will get close detailed attention instead 
of the usual sinkorswim training 
the initiative was announced tuesday by the american federation 
of teachers at the 744000member unions annual convention 
the schools selected by the union are norwood elementary in los 
angeles henry high school in minneapolis and marshall high school 
in rochester 
each school will receive 30000 in grants from the exxon 
education foundation 
starting next fall the schools will operate on much the same 
philosophy as teaching hospitals in the training of doctors said 
bruce goldberg codirector of the 2yearold aft center for 
restructuring 
currently most teacher trainees get sinkorswim training with 
occasional help from a mentor teacher 
the professional practice school model will give student 
teachers the opportunity to work in a clinical training site that 
supports collegiality and inquiry for students and teachers said 
aft president albert shanker 
the notion of transforming schools into teacher training centers 
has been supported by several teacher colleges in recent years 
said goldberg about 25 to 30 such collaborations have sprung up in 
the last couple of years he said 
