<TEXT>
businesses that use ozonedestroying 
chemicals in this city known for its hightech industries could 
face fines of up to 500 a day and sixmonth jail terms for their 
officers under a new law 
but many companies in this city of 90000 people about 40 miles 
south of los angeles may avoid the restrictions 
im expecting a fair number of exemptions at least in this 
first year michael brown the citys environmental coordinator 
said tuesday 
city officials hailed the measure as a local solution to a 
global problem when the city council approved it last summer the 
law went into effect sunday 
it prohibits companies from using or selling 
chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs and other chemicals that destroy 
ozone gas in the stratosphere about 30 to 50 miles above the 
earths surface 
ozone filters out ultraviolet radiation which can damage the 
human immune system cause skin cancer and cataracts harm crops 
and disrupt sea life 
scientists say restoring the ozone layer will require worldwide 
controls and 56 nations last week signed an agreement to ban some 
chemicals and set up a 240 million international fund through 
which industrialized nations can help developing countries adopt 
environmentally safer technology 
in the united states some states and localities have been in 
the forefront on ozone protection 
the connecticut general assembly last year banned the sale of 
freon in small containers to individuals for recharging 
refrigerators and car and home air conditioners but licensed 
repair people still can buy them similar legislation is pending in 
massachusetts 
more than a dozen counties and cities including irvine have 
enacted ordinances curtailing polystyrene in such uses as fastfood 
coffee cups and hamburger boxes since industry has modified its 
plasticsmaking process to use a much less ozonedepleting form of 
cfcs the primary benefit of these laws now is to keep landfills 
from overflowing 
irvine officials have yet to determine which companies are using 
cfcs and related chemicals that commonly serve as refrigerants and 
industrial solvents and are used in the manufacture of insulation 
foam and plastic food containers 
our best guess was that 200 to 300 were using cfcs brown 
said he estimated that as many as 100 will be granted exemptions 
because they have no alternative 
some such as hughes corps industrial electronics group 
division are legally bound to use solvents specified by contracts 
with the government 
companies that use solvents to make medical devices are 
similarly bound by us food and drug administration rules that 
certify a specific manufacturing process 
