<TEXT>
june 28 
the greenville sc news on the savings and loan collapse 
with great fanfare president bush last week made public a series 
of steps his administration will take to get tougher with criminals 
behind the financial collapse of hundreds of savings and loans 
institutions 
federal prosecutors will get more money manpower and legal 
authority to investigate and prosecute suspected cases of fraud 
the president said and we will not rest until the cheats and 
chiselers and charlatans have spent a large chunk of their lives 
behind the bars of a federal prison 
to a large degree bush was responding to the politics of the 
crisis democrats in congress have become strident in their 
criticism of his antifraud efforts and he has traded shots with 
them 
against this backdrop the new initiative and the we will not 
rest rhetoric ought to play well with a public that indeed is 
suspicious of the overall thrift industry rescue program now most 
should be mollified as long as no one expects too much 
estimates of the cost of restructuring the thrift industry range 
as high as 500 billion and most of that money is going to come 
from taxpayers 
investigators no doubt need more resources fbi field offices 
last year asked for 425 new agents they got 202 the us attorney 
in oklahoma has only five lawyers assigned to 40 investigations in 
oklahoma city bushs proposal to boost spending on fraud 
investigations to 100 million annually is in order but no one 
should expect an early or less costly rescue 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 2 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the jersey journal of jersey city nj on us supreme court 
ruling against political patronage 
whatever its merits as constitutional law the supreme court 
decision undercutting the validity of hiring and firing based on 
political patronage has the potential to perform a valuable service 
patronage has had as damaging an impact in hudson county as 
anywhere in america 
hiring rankandfile workers on the basis of political support 
or political activity severs the link between the individuals 
success in remaining employed getting promoted and getting 
favorable assignments and his or her performance on the job 
too many politicians have a vested interest in creating the jobs 
people want rather than the jobs people need 
the public especially in hudson county will be well served if 
reducing patronage produces more emphasis on doing the job well and 
less on serving the political ambitions of politicians and their 
partisan supporters 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 29 
the newsreview roseburg ore on math code 
the fact that a team of mathematicians has succeeded in 
splitting a 155digit number into its three prime factors is hardly 
the sort of news that has most people gripping the edges of their 
chairs nevertheless in the cryptologists arcane world of 
espionage and secret messages it is a major triumph only a year 
ago the feat seemed utterly impossible but researchers hendrik 
lenstra of the university of california at berkeley and john 
pollard of reading england have come close to confirming edgar 
allen poes famous dictum that human ingenuity cannot concoct a 
cipher which human ingenuity cannot resolve 
but what practical effect does this mathematical discovery have 
on the man in the street perhaps more than he realizes bankers 
use these large code numbers to move funds electronically phone 
companies use them to ensure privacy the defense department relies 
on them for security 
and governments use them to transmit secret intelligence 
breaking other nations codes produces more and better information 
than all the worlds spies put together 
 
no matter how good we become at solving codes military and 
diplomatic intelligence will always need to be backed up by another 
form of intelligence as the latest team of mathematicians has just 
shown there simply is no replacement for human ingenuity 
</TEXT>
