<TEXT>
july 2 
milwaukee sentinel on nasas hubble trouble 
a lot of travelers have known the disappointment of going on 
vacation only to find their camera is on the fritz but just 
imagine how the people who put up the hubble telescope must feel 
a problem with the lightgathering mirrors has partially 
distorted the 15 billion eye in the sky virtually eliminating 
its ability to single out dim and distant objects in space 
spokesmen for the national aeronautics and space administration 
say other functions of the hubble that are operating properly still 
justify the scientific mission of the venture 
but a probe of the problem should focus on how in the world the 
craft got off the ground with equipment that was not in tiptop 
shape 
perhaps an investigation will show that there was no way of 
catching the defect one person connected with the project already 
has said that the kind of testing necessary to spot it would have 
cost hundreds of millions of dollars 
but the project was 12 years in the making and experienced 
several delays and it is not enough to say that lack of money was 
the reason for the malfunction of a camera that was supposed to 
perform 40 percent of the crafts scientific work 
one report is that one of two precisely ground mirrors was not 
made to specification and the suggestion is that the problem was 
with the manufacturer but the public whose support for the 
project was sustained in part by the promise of pictures of 
neverbeforeseen stars deserves a thorough explanation 
the hope of course is that some of the lost capability of the 
hubble will be recaptured when a space shuttle team goes up to 
service the craft in april 1993 or given the new problem maybe 
sooner 
before they take off a double check should be made to make sure 
they have all the right tools along the history of the hubble is 
such that nothing can be taken for granted 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
june 30 
el paso texas heraldpost on drunken driving checkpoints 
the key word in the bill of rights protection against 
government harassment of individuals is unreasonable 
we suspect most americans agree with the supreme courts recent 
ruling that police checkpoints are a reasonable means of combating 
drunken driving 
interestingly our notion of what is unreasonable is sometimes 
irrational 
no fourth amendment challenge to electronic security checks at 
airports has reached the high court yet attacks on planes take 
infinitely fewer lives than drunken driving and airport security 
often involves more waiting than sobriety checkpoints along the 
road 
the effectiveness of checkpoints resides largely in deterrence 
the number of people who refrain from driving under the influence 
because of a checkpoint cannot be known 
organizations such as mothers against drunk driving have worked 
hard to raise the awareness of the routine cost of driving under 
the influence if they keep it up maybe 23000 deaths in a year 
will come to be seen as the scandal it is and more communities will 
crack down 
sobriety checkpoints should be among a communitys options 
</TEXT>
