<TEXT>
the armys task force smith peered through a 
steady rainfall on the morning of july 5 1950 and saw 33 oncoming 
sovietmade tanks and thousands of north korean infantrymen 
the unit had just six artillery shells powerful enough to 
penetrate heavy tank armor their bloody sevenhour rout is held 
up by the army 40 years later as an example of how not to fight a 
war 
task force smiths defeat is an object lesson for the 1990s 
declares gen carl e vuono the army chief of staff he says the 
army of 1950 was fractured by the rapid demobilization and meager 
budgets that followed the world war ii 
vuono says he fears that could repeat itself as the cold war 
recedes and political and budget pressures build to rapidly cut 
military spending 
the survivors of the illequipped task force smith units are 
convening for a reunion in nearby alexandria va thursday proud 
of their fight but resentful of the governmentcreated obstacles 
they faced 
the lesson from task force smith is that there is a need for a 
trained and ready army in times of peace especially when the army 
is small gen vuono said 
named for its commander ltcol charles bradford smith task 
force smith was hastily stitched together from infantry and 
artillery units after north korea struck across the 38th parallel 
on june 25 
on the morning of july 5 with north korean troops already in 
the south korean capital of seoul task force smith was dug in on a 
ridge commanding a highway and railway line about 22 miles south of 
seoul 
the first us combat unit to go into action in korea task 
force smith had problems weapons that didnt work inoperable 
radios no air support no resupply and no maps to lead troops to 
safety once the situation fell apart 
we found out we didnt have any weapons that could penetrate 
the armor on the tanks says william wyrick 65 a retired army 
colonel who was then a young first lieutenant leading a platoon 
the units highexplosive antitank or heat rounds represented 
one third of the armor piercing ammunition available in depots in 
japan 
those six rounds killed two tanks wyrick said in an 
telephone interview from his home in columbia sc 
but less powerful artillery shells simply bounced off the armor 
or didnt explode at all 
all we could do was scratch the tanks and annoy the gunners 
said carl bernard another retired army colonel who was a platoon 
leader with task force smith 
if we had been able to stop the tanks we would have been in a 
totally different world bernard said 
the vast majority of the weapons we carried into that fight 
had been declared combat unserviceable wyrick said our 
vehicles were worn out our radios didnt work because the 
batteries were corroded 
the north korean tanks sliced through task force smith during 
the first hour of fighting and continued their drive south 
elements of the north korean infantry crowded into a column of 
trucks that some accounts say formed a sixmilelong line attacked 
the us positions 
they were twice driven back wyrick said 
but by 230 in the afternoon we were running out of 
ammunition he said they were enveloping our flank and col 
smith gave the order to withdraw 
bernard never got the word and learned of the move only after a 
runner found the command post abandoned 
the withdrawal immediately became ragged and chaotic says 
author tr fehrenbach in his 1989 account of the korean war 
this kind of war a study in unpreparedness 
at close range automatic weapons chewed the retreating 
americans breaking them up into small disorganized units 
fehrenbach wrote they left their dead where they lay and 
abandoned the 30 or so wounded who were too hurt to walk 
of the more than 400 men who went into action with task force 
smith some 150 did not return 
we had no medical evacuation no resupply of food or 
ammunition wyrick said it was especially difficult because no 
one had a map the officers had only a general idea of where we 
were 
the two former lieutenants say their men lacked little in the 
way of fighting spirit but simply didnt have the resources to do 
the job 
i dont object to the way we fought i object to the result 
bernard said we didnt get anything like what we should have 
gotten 
</TEXT>
