<TEXT>
the united states is quietly improving 
relations with laos as that nations communist government shifts 
from state control of the economy and works to attract foreign 
private investment officials say 
the two nations are expanding joint efforts to combat drug 
smuggling and discussing the possibility of sending peace corps 
volunteers to the southeast asian nation officials say 
laos along with vietnam and cambodia came under communist rule 
in 1975 it was the only one of the three countries with which the 
us maintained diplomatic ties and with which there appears to be 
tangible progress toward friendly relations 
two decades ago us warplanes bombed laos for years in a 
failed effort to wipe out a communist insurgency but the rebels 
seized power within weeks after communist triumphs in vietnam and 
cambodia 
talks on sending peace corps volunteers are still in the 
preliminary stage us officials say with the focus on the type 
of experts the agency could send to laos the peace corps has never 
sent volunteers to a communist country although discussions had 
been held with china before sinoamerican relations soured last 
year 
last fall the united states and laos agreed on a development 
aid project the first anywhere in indochina in 15 years the 87 
million effort is aimed at persuading farmers in northeast laos to 
cultivate crops other than opium 
linked to that project was an agreement signed last january in 
which laos promised a maximum effort to halt the cultivation 
and trafficking of opium 
laos also has been more cooperative in helping the us 
government obtain an accounting for american servicemen killed 
there during the vietnam war 
the collaboration has included inspections in remote areas by 
teams of laotians and americans and visits to sites where us war 
planes crashed 
in addition laos has lifted restrictions on travel by us 
diplomats in its capital of vientiane and on the number of 
americans authorized to serve there 
the two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since the 
communist victory but discussions on a possible exchange have 
begun us officials said 
the whole dialogue has improved said one us official who 
insisted that he not be identified 
the conciliation effort has been made easier by a substantial 
reduction in the number of vietnamese troops stationed in laos 
which had long been seen as the junior partner in its alliance with 
vietnam 
us officials estimate there were once as many as 40000 to 
50000 vietnamese troops in laos only a handful at most remain 
they say 
beyond that laos has set free virtually all of the several 
thousand political prisoners confined to labor camps after the 
communist victory the officials said 
perhaps the most significant change relates to laoss effort to 
revitalize its moribund economy the officials said 
laos has been selling off state enterprises and moving toward a 
private economy with a heavy reliance on foreign investment 
the shifts began after laos appeared to be falling increasingly 
behind the dynamic economies elsewhere in the region including 
neighboring thailand 
</TEXT>
