<TEXT>
as nato leaders ponder the alliances future 
president bush is cast somewhere between margaret thatchers 
cautious approach and helmut kohls pursuit of conciliation with 
moscow 
the arrangement gives bush tremendous power to influence the 
outcome of the twoday strategic review in london as it is us 
presidents by virtue of americas historic might tend to dominate 
such sessions anyhow 
even before the 16 nato nations assembled in london word leaked 
out that bush was willing to consider scrapping 1470 us 
nucleartipped artillery shells and 1560 us tactical nuclear 
bombs in light of a diminished soviet threat and a disintegrating 
warsaw pact 
also the strategic doctrine that has guided natos policies for 
over four decades was due for an overhaul because a blitzkrieg by 
the red army is less likely than ever the allies are ready to make 
the use of nuclear weapons an option of last resort this flips the 
existing firstuse theory upside down to reflect new military 
realities in europe 
and yet even though bush sent letters to the other leaders 
before the summit outlining his proposals there was a lot of room 
left for debate and for decision in london 
this is not a precooked summit meeting a us official 
said that wouldnt bring about the best results 
when the debate breaks out circumspectly behind closed doors 
it is quite likely that mrs thatcher britains prime minister 
will make the argument for keeping natos guard up it is equally 
likely that kohl the chancellor of west germany will emphasize 
that the eastwest relationship must be sharply changed to reflect 
the ending of the cold war 
communism has crumbled it has lost all credibility even 
among nominal believers mrs thatcher told the nato foreign 
ministers at a presummit session june 7 in turnberry scotland 
and yet she said europes future is bound to be turbulent and 
uncertain 
we must keep our capacity effectively to deter and to defend 
ourselves she said you dont cancel your home insurance 
policy just because there have been fewer burglaries in your street 
in the last 12 months 
of the other nato leaders president francois mitterrand of 
france is perhaps most inclined to support mrs thatchers cautious 
approach 
on the other end of the spectrum is kohl backed by a foreign 
minister hansdietrich genscher who has taken the lead in trying 
to allay soviet and polish concerns about the impending west german 
absorption of east germany 
these assurances include a pledge not to develop german nuclear 
chemical or biological weapons permitting the red army to remain 
for a transitional period on what is now east german territory and 
keeping nato forces out of that region in the meantime 
the bush administration has endorsed this approach but steered 
clear so far of west germanys economic inducements to moscow 
including an aid package that might be put together with other west 
european governments 
bush did say wednesday however he would look more favorably 
upon western economic aid to moscow if the kremlin slashed spending 
on defense 
i hope that given the changes in the world theyll be able to 
curtail that defense spending some he told reporters in 
kennebunkport maine his summer vacation retreat just hours 
before leaving for london 
gesncher speaking at a may 27 university of marylandeuropean 
branch commencement proclaimed that a united germany will remain 
in nato 
however he also said that the development of a 
stabilityoriented partnership with the soviet union and other 
european countries is the right perspective for the atlantic 
alliance 
genscher is for broadening the role of the 35nation conference 
on security and cooperation in europe csce which deals with 
military security economic cooperation and human rights 
the csce process must be intensified and given permanent 
institutional foundations he said 
a new relationship between nato and the warsaw pact must be 
developed to open up new possibilities for the development of 
relations with the soviet union genscher said 
on the nuclear issue meanwhile kohl and genscher tend to 
reflect the anxieties of a german populace faced with the largest 
concentration of nuclear weapons in the world 
this has contributed to west germanys conciliatory approach 
perhaps as much as bonns eagerness for unification 
all these conflicting views and national pressures will be close 
to the surface at the nato summit as the alliance begins to change 
its focus from a military to a political forum 
on the one side there is mrs thatcher adamant that natos 
future role is to remain a defense alliance bolstered with nuclear 
weapons and us troops 
to reinforce this stand britain is replacing its aging nuclear 
weapons with us trident missiles 
sufficient forces and weapons keep us secure not fine 
words she said in turnberry 
chancellor kohl meanwhile agrees that us troops should 
remain in west germany but his government was the principal force 
within nato for delaying the deployment of new us shortrange 
nuclear missiles and in may bush scrapped the program for 
installing new lances 
which side will bush come down on in london 
administration officials prefer casting the question differently 
the united states an official said is trying to provide 
a pole of consensus around which the alliance can rally 
</TEXT>
