<TEXT>
marion rice hart an adventurer who 
sailed around the world and made seven solo flights across the 
atlantic has died of pneumonia she was 98 
hart who died monday first learned to fly at age 54 and earned 
worldwide acclaim for her feats 
i wanted to see the world i dont want to just sit around the 
house the then81yearold hart told a reporter in 1972 before 
she climbed into her singleengine aircraft in katmandu nepal 
the feminist movement didnt mean much to her because she did 
whatever she wanted before feminism came in said her niece 
dorothy rice 
hart was born oct 2 1891 in london she married a mining 
engineer and the couple lived in arizona and california before 
divorcing 
after learning to fly hart piloted her singleengine plane 
nonstop across the atlantic at age 61 
she later flew all over the united states europe asia africa 
and south america and made at least six more solo flights across 
the atlantic the last at age 83 
she always wanted to get into russia said dorothy rice 
she wrote to mrs khrushchev but they would only permit it if 
she had a soviet guide and she never wanted that she refused 
hart received the harmon international trophy from vice 
president walter mondale in 1976 the award recognized her feats 
operating a small aircraft on a global scale 
hart whose parents left her a comfortable trust fund was the 
first woman to graduate in chemical engineering from the 
massachusetts institute of technology 
in 1936 hart cast off for what became a threeyear voyage 
sailing around the world on her 72foot ketch 
hart took to flying after working as a radio operator for the 
army air corps during world war ii she stopped flying at age 87 
after she overshot the runway at the tucson ariz airport on a 
trip back from mexico the plane is in the tucson pima air museum 
hart is survived by one nephew and four nieces at her request 
no funeral service will be held 
</TEXT>
