<TEXT>
pratt amp whitney has recalled more than 
three dozen of its newest largest jet engines in response to a 
compressor problem that if left unchecked could have prompted an 
inflight engine shutdown 
the problem was discovered in one pw4000 engine compressor 
pratt spokesman mark sullivan said tuesday he said none of the 
recalled engines was in use by an airline 
the problem stemmed from a tightening of the bladetip clearance 
in the engines highpressure compressor a performance 
improvement pratt introduced in february sullivan said the 
reduced clearance meant rotating compressor blades were rubbing a 
bit harder against rub strips inside the engine casing 
although there were no problems in ground testing for the first 
38 improvedperformance engines the 39th engine had excessive rub 
causing the compressor to stall 
sullivan said east hartfordbased pratt amp whitney a division of 
hartfortbased united technologies corp is satisfied that the 
problem has been corrected he said the problem caused a very 
minimal disruption to our customers and their delivery schedules 
pratt has been marketing the pw4000 engine for the many jumbo 
jets expected to enter service in the 1990s the first 38 engines 
had been shipped to aircraft builders boeing co in seattle 
mcdonnell douglas corp in long beach calif and airbus industrie 
in toulouse france sullivan said 
to replace the recalled engines pratt delivered new pw4000s 
with the original bladetip clearance sullivan said 
