<TEXT>
germany will send a single team to the 1992 
olympics the presidents of the two national olympic committees 
announced wednesday 
it will be the first time since the 1964 olympic games in tokyo 
that germany will compete with a unified team and the merger is 
expected to make the already strong german teams a powerhouse 
single unit 
willi daume president of the west german olympic committee and 
joachim weiskopf president of the counterpart east german 
organization said the two national olympic committees will merge 
in december to oversee the formation of a single team 
the merger will follow the political unification of the two 
german states expected in early december 
a united german team may be competing in international athletics 
as early as march 1991 authorities in east berlin said 
the two olympic committee presidents said there was complete 
agreement between the two organisations about the decision 
we had no dissenting opinions whatsoever daum said at a 
news conference in east berlin 
the unification will be completed by the two olympic 
committees in an orderly fashion we will be working intensively 
together in the coming weeks daume said 
were moving ahead quickly for the sake of the athletes a 
fast merger is important in order to remove any uncertainty about 
who will make the team said weiskopf 
as the two germanys grow together there has been great concern 
over whether the athletes would feel shorted out of the competition 
for fewer places still we find great support among our sportsmen 
for forming one team from one country he said 
weiskopf said it was not yet clear how the team would be 
selected and funded he also said the international sport governing 
bodies would need to decide how a single german team would be 
represented in qualifying competitions for world and olympic events 
separate teams representing both the national olympic committees 
have already participated in qualifying events in some sports 
these events determine the rank and seeding for teams in major 
competitions such as the world championships in individual sports 
and the olympic games 
both olympic committee presidents also said they support the 
choice of berlin as site of the olympics in 2000 
the city of berlin should be accepted by the international 
olympic committee for athletic and humanitarian reasons said 
daume 
the groups with active participation by athletes will develop 
plans for the formation of a team for the 1992 olympic games in 
albertville france and barcelona spain 
east germany won 127 medals at the olympic games in 1988 and 
west germany won 48 together a united german team would have won 
175 14 medals more than firstplace soviet union 
in the tokyo games in 1964 the single german team competed 
under the olympic flag with the olympic anthem 
it is the place for sports to lead in this direction it is a 
great step towards peace weiskopf said 
