romania and bulgaria on wednesday 
moved to resolve an ecological dispute that has long soured 
relations between them 
prime ministers petre roman of romania and andrei lukanov of 
bulgaria agreed at a meeting to set up a joint commission that will 
work toward diminishing and stopping the pollution caused by the 
giurgiu chemical plant and the bulgarian nuclear facility near the 
border 
the two sides undertook to provide each other with exact data on 
the disputed facilities within 20 days and to complete a convention 
for protecting the environment along their border before august 
they said world experts will be asked to assess the degree of 
pollution at the frontier and the measures necessary for removing 
the pollution 
the agreement was announced in a communique released after the 
meeting 
thousands of bulgarians demonstrated along the frontier last 
month demanding closure of the giurgiu plant 
romanians in turn accused the bulgarians of having insufficient 
safety standards at their nearby nuclear plant 
