<DOCNO> AP900704-0153 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
businesses not individuals are becoming the 
victims of choice in the thriving crime of telephone fraud 
industry experts believe 
phone fraud accounts for 500 million in losses or about 1 
percent of the 50 billion in revenues earned by long distance 
carriers annually says the communications fraud control 
association a mclean vabased group 
traditionally long distance ripoffs consisted mainly of calling 
card fraud mostly unauthorized use of individuals or businesses 
carrierissued calling card billing numbers other phone service 
thieves used socalled black boxes that emit a tone to allow 
access to long distance lines 
but individual calling card fraud is being taken over rapidly by 
another scam one that victimizes business telephone systems 
called private branch exchanges or pbxs 
abusers are now going after the more vulnerable pbxs and are 
having a field day said rami abuhamdeh whose association is 
financed by telephone companies and law enforcement agencies 
pbx scams target a feature on the phone system that allows 
company employees to dial into the home office usually on an 800 
or wats line from outside then after punching in a personal 
identification number they get a second dial tone and can make 
calls as if they were sitting at their desk 
calls made using this feature called reorigination allow the 
company to save the additional charges that long distance carriers 
assess for calling card use 
to get the 3to4 digit security codes computer hackers use 
programs on their own personal computers equipped with a telephone 
modem they can automatically dial numbers sequentially until they 
hit upon the right combination to access an outgoing line 
a hacker can even start the program before he goes to bed and by 
the time he wakes up in the morning hell have hacked out the code 
number said bob fox of united telecomus sprint 
abuhamdeh claims that thieves are targetting pbxs in part 
because larger long distance companies have beefed up their 
security against calling card fraud 
access codes also have been sold by disgruntled employees at 
some companies 
according to fox calling card fraud at us sprint is down to 
insignificant numbers but for businesses victimized by pbx fraud 
losses can be staggering 
fox said 30000 to 40000 in extra charges are not unusual 
abuhamdeh said new york citys human resources administration 
lost 700000 in two months after someone inside the agency sold 
codes to outsiders 
among the most innovative attempts at eliminating remote access 
fraud is a device developed by us sprint that can recognize the 
precise voice pattern of a legitimate customer 
the customer after registering his voice pattern with the long 
distance carrier simply says his identification number into the 
phone and the voice recognition device verifies the users identity 
it applies to both long distance comanies and pbx users the 
technology is at point right now where its changing every day and 
becoming better abuhamdeh said 
companies can take immediate steps to fight against pbx fraud by 
increasing remote access code numbers to as many digits as the 
system allows and not using numbers in sequential order fox says 
fox also recommends that companies turn off the reorigination 
feature of a pbx during hours when it is not normally used and 
review remote access records as frequently as possible 
voice recognition systems and pbx fraud were among the main 
items on the agenda of the communications fraud control 
associations annual conference last month in pentaggon city va 
over 150 attendees representing more than 100 firms and 
organizations participated in the conference 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

