two dozen rich nations wednesday 
extended their aid program for poland and hungary to four other 
east european nations that have shed their communist ways for 
freemarket economies 
the countries remained divided on the question of extending aid 
to the soviet union however west germany wants quick action on 
such aid while the united states and japan want to wait for further 
reforms there 
the agreement to grant financial aid to bulgaria yugoslavia 
czechoslovakia and east germany came at a meeting of foreign 
ministers of the oranization for economic cooperation and 
development a parisbased group of industrial democracies 
the ministers excluded romania from the aid package because of 
doubts about its commitment to democratic reforms 
wednesdays meeting did not fix specific aid figures these will 
emerge in the months ahead as each donor makes its own pledges in 
food money credits loan guarantees and other assistance 
it was a conference designed to take stock see whether we 
should and could decided to add countries to the aid package 
british foreign secretary douglas hurd told reporters 
aid to the new east european beneficiaries is bound to run into 
billions of dollars in the long term 
already the 24 donor nations have pledged more than 124 
billion in food economic and environmental aid to poland and 
hungary since they began coordinating their aid program last summer 
the aid effort is coordinated by the european community 
commission the executive body for the group of 12 west european 
countries 
in a communique the ministers said the four additional 
beneficiaries of aid merited help in view of the reforms they have 
begun based on the rule of law the respect of human rights the 
introduction of multiparty systems the holding of free and fair 
elections and the establishment of market economies 
of romania where newly elected officials relied on miners last 
month to suppress antigovernment protests they said 
recent events in romania have not created the conditions in 
which the implementation of coordinated assistance should be 
extended to that country under present circumstances 
aid to the soviet union will be discussed at next weeks summit 
of the leaders of the worlds seven most industrialized nations in 
houston texas the issue also is under review within the ec 
we cannot expect the soviet union to resolve problems 
regarding the transition to a market economy on their own west 
german foreign minister hansdietrich genscher told reporters 
