<TEXT>
the world economy is slowing down and 
growth has virtually halted in eastern europe and the soviet union 
as some governments undertake drastic marketoriented reform a 
un study says 
the 1990 world economic survey released tuesday says world 
economic output increased by 31 percent in 1989 compared with 44 
percent in 1988 
industrialized market economies continued to expand growing by 
35 percent and although the figure was lower than the 43 percent 
of 1988 it was stronger than had been expected the report says 
economic growth in the developing world as a whole slowed from 
45 percent in 1988 to 34 percent in 1989 economic performance 
varied greatly by region 
the report agreed in general with the findings of the 
parisbased organization for economic cooperation and development 
which said last week that the economies of the industrialized world 
remain on a steady course 
like the oecd report it warned against inflation especially in 
east european countries that are changing from statecontrolled to 
market economies 
economic growth in eastern europe and the soviet union came to 
a virtual halt in 1989 the report says adding that output 
increased by just 12 percent 
un economists said they do not expect a bright picture for the 
immediate future in countries restructuring their economies 
although the longterm prospects could improve with painful reform 
the danger of rapid inflation in the reforming socialist 
countries is a major concern says the report requiring 
prudent monetary and fiscal policies during the transition to more 
marketoriented economies 
in several latin american countries hyperinflation is a serious 
problem it says and stabilization policies are likely to prove 
costly in the short term longterm prospects are uncertain 
the survey compiled by the un department of international 
economic and social affairs says the economies of south and east 
asia grew by 62 percent last yeasr compared with 82 percent in 
1988 the survey said 
chinas growth rate delined sharply from 114 percent in 1988 
to 39 percent in 1989 
latin america and the caribbean saw just a 07 percent increase 
and per capita output fell for the second consecutive year 
inflation was unprecedented in the region 
in africa economies expanded by 28 percent in 1989 below the 
rate of population growth and per capita output fell as a result 
in west asia economic recovery continued with a 25 percent 
growth rate economic stabilization measures stalled growth in 
mediterranean countries 
the survey proposed establishment of a central european payments 
union similar to the european payments union established after 
world war ii as a temporary measure to assist reforming eastern 
european countries in their transition to marketoriented economies 
with convertible currencies 
