<DOCNO> AP900704-0171 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
oil companies operating in the united states 
relied more on foreign production than domestic and spent more 
money overseas to look for new oil for the first time last year 
according to an industry survey 
the shift reflects the steady decline in domestic oil production 
in recent years in part a consequence of relatively weak world oil 
prices and increased concerns about the environmental impact of 
oil exploration and production in the united states the survey 
released tuesday by arthur andersen amp co said 
the broad conclusion we can draw from this years study is 
that the world oil industry is entering a new era and us 
exploration and production companies are successfully adapting to 
the changing environment said victor a burk managing director 
of oil and gas industry services for arthur andersen 
for the first time last year the companies surveyed had greater 
foreign oil reserves than domestic reserves saw oil production 
from foreign sources surpass domestic production and spent more on 
exploration and production for new oil overseas than in the united 
states 
the 11th annual study is based on data on reserve quantity 
value cost and other details filed with the securities and 
exchange commission by 236 public companies for the five years from 
1985 through 1989 
companies in the study included us and canadian firms and 
three major foreign companies with significant us operations 
british petroleum royal dutchshell and broken hill proprietary of 
australia 
in 1989 the companies in the study accounted for more than 60 
percent of the total proved oil and gas reserves and production in 
the united states 
the united states has been the most heavily explored country in 
the world burk said companies are shifting their exploration focus 
abroad because they believe the chances of bigger finds are 
better 
they believe the opportunities right now are greater outside 
the united states he said 
the driving forces behind the changing industry environment 
include continuing declines in us oil production coupled with an 
increase in reliance on imports the dramatic political and 
economic changes in the soviet union and eastern europe and reduced 
soviet oil production and rapid economic growth and oil demand in 
east asian countries burk said 
in addition environmental concerns will fundamentally change 
oil transportation offshore exploration refining and utility and 
industrial fuel choices he said 
major companies are using this period to rationalize their 
asset portfolios and expand foreign operations he said this 
in turn creates new opportunities for us independents in 
acquiring and exploring for reserves taking advantage of technical 
innovations and further improving operating efficiencies 
burk also said that in 1989 there was a further reduction in 
domestic finding costs to an average 724 a decline of 103 or 
125 percent per barrel 
foreign finding costs registered a decline of almost 9 percent 
to 873 
</TEXT>
